post.summary: Creates a webhook.
post.description:
A webhook is an HTTP endpoint that the API client must implement to receive notifications of access events, occurrences, and other types of events.

A webhook has a buffer of events that are queued in real time. A webhook executes a loop to send the events from the queue. At each iteration, the buffer is emptied and events are discarded.

If a webhook takes more than 30 seconds to respond, the request is canceled.

When the webhook buffer is full, the events are discarded.

The json has the following format:

	{
	  "name": "Teste",
	  "token": "1234",
	  "events": [
		{
		  "type": "access",
		  "dateTime": "2019-02-15T17:21:48.778011-02:00",
		  "id": 1891,
		  "accountId": 1000,
		  "zoneId": 1001,
		  "serverId": 1000,
		  "doorId": 1,
		  "personId": 1,
		  "direction": 1,
		  "authorized": true,
		  "openingType": 7
		},
		{
		  "type": "access",
		  "dateTime": "2019-02-15T17:21:48.778011-02:00",
		  "id": 1892,
		  "accountId": 1000,
		  "zoneId": 1001,
		  "serverId": 1000,
		  "doorId": 2,
		  "personId": 2,
		  "direction": 2,
		  "authorized": true,
		  "openingType": 7
		}
	  ]
	}
	
See the endpoint 'POST /api/webhooks/help' for more information about the events.
